{"title_page": "Joan Chandler", "text_new": "{{short description|American actor}}\n{{refimprove|date=March 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n|image        = Joan Chandler in Rope trailer.jpg \n|image_size   =\n|caption      = from the trailer for the film ''Rope'' (1948)\n|birth_name   = Joan Cheeseman\n|birth_date   = {{Birth date|1923|8|24}}\n|birth_place  = [[Butler, Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n|death_date   = {{Death date and age|1979|5|11|1923|8|24}}\n|death_place  = New York City, U.S.\n|occupation   = Film, stage, television actress\n| alma_mater  = [[Bennington College]]\n|years_active = 1944&ndash;1960\n|spouse       = David McKay<br>Dr. Charles C. Hogan\n}}\n\n'''Joan Chandler''' (born '''Joan Cheeseman'''; August 24, 1923 \u2013 May 11, 1979) was an American actress who notably starred in ''[[Rope (film)|Rope]]'' (1948) with [[James Stewart]] and ''[[Humoresque (1946 film)|Humoresque]]'' (1946) with [[Joan Crawford]].\n\nThe daughter of Mr. and Mrs. Carl Cheesman, Chandler was born in [[Butler, Pennsylvania]]. She took piano lessons from her musician mother and began studying ballet when she was 5. She attended [[Butler Senior High School|Butler High School]]<ref name=pp120146>{{cite news |title=Butler Actress Makes Debut in 'Humoresque' |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47704875/joan-chandler/ |accessdate=March 31, 2020 |work=The Pittsburgh Press |date=December 1, 1946 |location=Pennsylvania, Pittsburgh |page=17|via = [[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref> and the School of Arts at [[Bennington College]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Ambition fulfilled |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47702219/joan-chandler/ |accessdate=March 31, 2020 |work=The Pittsburgh Press |date=January 5, 1947 |location=Pennsylvania, Pittsburgh |page=59|via = [[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref> She also studied at the [[Neighborhood Playhouse School of the Theatre]] in New York.<ref name=pp120146/> Before she became a professional actress, Chandler toured with a ballet company.<ref>{{cite news |title=Joan Chandler Signed To Contract by Warner's |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47705901/joan-chandler/ |accessdate=March 31, 2020 |work=Tampa Bay Times |date=September 16, 1945 |location=Florida, St. Petersburg |page=34|via = [[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref>\n\nA founding member of [[Actors Studio|The Actors Studio]],<ref>{{cite book|quote=Also [in Lewis' class were] Henry Barnard, Jay Barney, John Becher, Philip Bourneuf, Joan Chandler, Peter Cookson, Stephen Elliott, Robert Emhardt, Joy Geffen, William Hansen, Will Hare, Jane Hoffman, George Keane, Don Keefer, George Matthews, Peggy Meredith, Ty Perry, Margaret Phillips, David Pressman, William Prince, Elliot Reid, Frances Reid, Kurt Richards, Elizabeth Ross, Thelma Schnee, Joshua Shelley, Fed Stewart, John Straub, Michael Strong, John Sylvester, Julie Warren, Mary Welch, Lois Wheeler, and William Woodson.|first=David |last=Garfield|title=A Player's Place: The Story of The Actors Studio|url=https://archive.org/details/playersplacestor00garf|url-access=registration|year=1980|publisher=MacMillan Publishing Co., Inc.|location=New York|isbn=0-02-542650-8|page=[https://archive.org/details/playersplacestor00garf/page/52 52]|chapter=Birth of The Actors Studio: 1947-1950}}</ref> Chandler appeared in several feature films, five Broadway plays, and about 12 television programs, such as ''[[Studio One (radio-TV series)|Studio One]]'' and ''Starlight Theatre''. She was married twice, first to David McKay, with whom she had one daughter, and then to Dr. Charles C. Hogan. Both marriages ended in divorce.<ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite news|last1=Cook|first1=Joan|title=Joan Chandler Dead: Played on Broadway in My Three Angels|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1979/05/15/archives/joan-chandler-dead-played-on-broadway-in-my-three-angels-in.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=15 May 1979|page=B8}}</ref>\n\nChandler died at age 55 of cancer{{fact|date=May 2018}} in New York City.\n\n==Filmography==\n\n* ''[[Humoresque (1946 film)|Humoresque]]'' (1946) - Gina Romney\n* ''[[Rope (film)|Rope]]'' (1948) - Janet Walker\n* ''[[Dragstrip Riot]]'' (1958)\n\n==Television==\n{{div col|colwidth=26em}}\n*''[[Philco Television Playhouse]]'' (1 episode, 1949)\n:- \"[[The House of the Seven Gables]]\" (1949) TV episode\n*''[[Actors Studio (TV series)|Actors Studio]]'' (1 episode, 1950)\n:- Sanctuary in Paris (1950) TV episode\n*''Starlight Theatre'' (1 episode, 1950)\n:- The Roman Kid (1950) TV episode\n*''[[Pulitzer Prize Playhouse]]'' (1 episode, 1951) - Hester\n:- The Silver Cord (1951) TV episode\n*''[[Somerset Maugham|Somerset Maugham TV Theatre]]'' (1 episode, 1951)\n:- The Romantic Young Lady (1951) TV episode\n*''[[Armstrong Circle Theatre]]'' (1 episode, 1951)\n:- A Different World (1951) TV episode\n*''[[Celanese Theatre]]'' (1 episode, 1951) - Miriamne\n:- \"[[Winterset (play)|Winterset]]\" (1951) TV episode\n*''[[Suspense (US TV series)|Suspense]]'' (1 episode, 1951)\n:- Mikki (1951) TV episode\n*''[[Robert Montgomery Presents]]'' (1 episode, 1952)\n:- The Closed Door (1952) TV episode\n*''[[Four Star Playhouse]]'' (1 episode, 1954)\n:- Detective's Holiday (1954) TV episode\n*''[[Westinghouse Studio One]]'' (2 episodes, 1950\u20131956)\n:- Song for a Summer Night (1956) TV episode\n:- Spectre of Alexander Wolff (1950) TV episode\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Plays==\n{{div col|colwidth=26em}}\n*''[[The Disenchanted]]'' (Breit-Schulberg)\n:Performer: Joan Chandler (Jere Halliday) - Replacement - [[Eugene O'Neill Theatre|Coronet Theatre]] - December 3, 1958 to May 16, 1959\t\n*''[[The Tempest]]'' (William  Shakespeare)\n:Starring: Joan Chandler (Miranda) - [[American Shakespeare Festival]] - August 1, 1955 to September 3, 1955\n*''[[My Three Angels]]'' (Samuel and Bella Spewack)\n:Starring: Joan Chandler (Marie Louise Ducotel) - [[Morosco Theatre]] - March 11, 1953 to January 2, 1954\n*''[[The Lady from the Sea|The Lady From the Sea]]'' (Ibsen)\n:Performer: Joan Chandler (Boletta) - [[Fulton Theatre]] - August 7, 1950 to August 19, 1950\n*''[[Where's Charley?]]'' (Loesser-Abbott)\n:Starring: Joan Chandler (Amy Spettigue) - Replacement - musical based on ''[[Charley's Aunt]]'' - [[St. James Theatre]] - October 11, 1948 to September 9, 1950\n*''[[The Late George Apley]]''\n:Performer: Joan Chandler (Eleanor Apley) - based on the novel by [[J. P. Marquand]] - opened on Broadway at the [[Lyceum Theatre (Broadway)|Lyceum Theatre]] on November 23, 1944, and ran for 384 performances\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{IMDb name|0151401}}\n* {{IBDB name}}\n* [http://archives.nypl.org/the/22466 Joan Chandler papers, 1923-1959], held by the Billy Rose Theatre Division, [[New York Public Library for the Performing Arts]]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chandler, Joan}}\n[[Category:1923 births]]\n[[Category:1979 deaths]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American stage actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:People from Butler, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in New York (state)]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American actor}}\n{{refimprove|date=March 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n|image        = Joan Chandler in Rope trailer.jpg \n|image_size   =\n|caption      = from the trailer for the film ''Rope'' (1948)\n|birth_name   = Joan Cheeseman\n|birth_date   = {{Birth date|1923|8|24}}\n|birth_place  = [[Butler, Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n|death_date   = {{Death date and age|1979|5|11|1923|8|24}}\n|death_place  = New York City, U.S.\n|occupation   = Film, stage, television actress\n| alma_mater  = [[Bennington College]]\n|years_active = 1944&ndash;1960\n|spouse       = David McKay<br>Dr. Charles C. Hogan\n}}\n\n'''Joan Chandler''' (born '''Joan Cheeseman'''; August 24, 1923 \u2013 May 11, 1979) was an American actress who notably starred in ''[[Rope (film)|Rope]]'' (1948) with [[James Stewart]] and ''[[Humoresque (1946 film)|Humoresque]]'' (1946) with [[Joan Crawford]].\n\nThe daughter of Mr. and Mrs. Carl Cheesman, Chandler was born in [[Butler, Pennsylvania]]. Sbe took piano lessons from her musician mother and began studying ballet when she was 5. She attended [[Butler Senior High School|Butler High School]]<ref name=pp120146>{{cite news |title=Butler Actress Makes Debut in 'Humoresque' |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47704875/joan-chandler/ |accessdate=March 31, 2020 |work=The Pittsburgh Press |date=December 1, 1946 |location=Pennsylvania, Pittsburgh |page=17|via = [[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref> and the School of Arts at [[Bennington College]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Ambition fulfilled |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47702219/joan-chandler/ |accessdate=March 31, 2020 |work=The Pittsburgh Press |date=January 5, 1947 |location=Pennsylvania, Pittsburgh |page=59|via = [[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref> She also studied at the [[Neighborhood Playhouse School of the Theatre]] in New York.<ref name=pp120146/> Before she became a professional actress, Chandler toured with a ballet company.<ref>{{cite news |title=Joan Chandler Signed To Contract by Warner's |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47705901/joan-chandler/ |accessdate=March 31, 2020 |work=Tampa Bay Times |date=September 16, 1945 |location=Florida, St. Petersburg |page=34|via = [[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref>\n\nA founding member of [[Actors Studio|The Actors Studio]],<ref>{{cite book|quote=Also [in Lewis' class were] Henry Barnard, Jay Barney, John Becher, Philip Bourneuf, Joan Chandler, Peter Cookson, Stephen Elliott, Robert Emhardt, Joy Geffen, William Hansen, Will Hare, Jane Hoffman, George Keane, Don Keefer, George Matthews, Peggy Meredith, Ty Perry, Margaret Phillips, David Pressman, William Prince, Elliot Reid, Frances Reid, Kurt Richards, Elizabeth Ross, Thelma Schnee, Joshua Shelley, Fed Stewart, John Straub, Michael Strong, John Sylvester, Julie Warren, Mary Welch, Lois Wheeler, and William Woodson.|first=David |last=Garfield|title=A Player's Place: The Story of The Actors Studio|url=https://archive.org/details/playersplacestor00garf|url-access=registration|year=1980|publisher=MacMillan Publishing Co., Inc.|location=New York|isbn=0-02-542650-8|page=[https://archive.org/details/playersplacestor00garf/page/52 52]|chapter=Birth of The Actors Studio: 1947-1950}}</ref> Chandler appeared in several feature films, five Broadway plays, and about 12 television programs, such as ''[[Studio One (radio-TV series)|Studio One]]'' and ''Starlight Theatre''. She was married twice, first to David McKay, with whom she had one daughter, and then to Dr. Charles C. Hogan. Both marriages ended in divorce.<ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite news|last1=Cook|first1=Joan|title=Joan Chandler Dead: Played on Broadway in My Three Angels|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1979/05/15/archives/joan-chandler-dead-played-on-broadway-in-my-three-angels-in.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=15 May 1979|page=B8}}</ref>\n\nChandler died at age 55 of cancer{{fact|date=May 2018}} in New York City.\n\n==Filmography==\n\n* ''[[Humoresque (1946 film)|Humoresque]]'' (1946) - Gina Romney\n* ''[[Rope (film)|Rope]]'' (1948) - Janet Walker\n* ''[[Dragstrip Riot]]'' (1958)\n\n==Television==\n{{div col|colwidth=26em}}\n*''[[Philco Television Playhouse]]'' (1 episode, 1949)\n:- \"[[The House of the Seven Gables]]\" (1949) TV episode\n*''[[Actors Studio (TV series)|Actors Studio]]'' (1 episode, 1950)\n:- Sanctuary in Paris (1950) TV episode\n*''Starlight Theatre'' (1 episode, 1950)\n:- The Roman Kid (1950) TV episode\n*''[[Pulitzer Prize Playhouse]]'' (1 episode, 1951) - Hester\n:- The Silver Cord (1951) TV episode\n*''[[Somerset Maugham|Somerset Maugham TV Theatre]]'' (1 episode, 1951)\n:- The Romantic Young Lady (1951) TV episode\n*''[[Armstrong Circle Theatre]]'' (1 episode, 1951)\n:- A Different World (1951) TV episode\n*''[[Celanese Theatre]]'' (1 episode, 1951) - Miriamne\n:- \"[[Winterset (play)|Winterset]]\" (1951) TV ep